        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Time Constraints:
Observation IS TIME CONSTRAINED as it must be conducted within
Jun1-July1, 2014.   The OT time constrained box is set to NO only because an OT would otherwise generate an (incorrect) error.  The time range corresponds to science requirements for (1) Venus phase (0.75-0.85), and (2) Imaging across AM (not PM) terminator.  Jun1-July1, 2014 also corresponds to Venus disc size small enough to satisfy ALMA maximum spatial scale constraints (see below).

Science requires Venus phase 0.75-0.85 in order to observe a Venus local time range that includes sufficient fractions of both day and nightside to adequately map the cross-terminator day/night transition.

Maximum Spatial Scale:
Jun1-July1, 2014 corresponds to Venus diameter 12"-14".   We therefore require both 12-m and ACA observations, for spatial scale recovery up to 12".  For the special case of planets, observations of disk size up to 15" is justified as follows 
(Butler &amp; Bastion, 1999): 
Data analysis will include modeling a priori knowledge of large scale planetary brightness (eg. limb darkening). This, together with the nominal 12" 12-m/ACA maximum scale enables understanding of spatial variation up to 15''.  Team members Sagawa, Gurwell, Butler, and Moullet have extensive experience in the required modeling.

Backend: 
Band 7 is required. Dual polarization observations (of these unpolarized absorptions) provide best sensitivity.   The 346.58 GHz window includes SO, SO2, and H2SO4 lines, such that the three molecules are observed simultaneously.  

At pressures corresponding to the relevant altitude range, frequency resolutions of 300 KHz or better for the 346.58 and 335.39 GHz windows are appropriate for retrieving altitude distributions from shape of the pressure broadened absorptions.   Freq. resolution better than 200 KHz is needed for the 12CO window, for retrieval of winds at higher altitude, where thermal (rather than pressure) broadening controls line shape.

Two spectral windows are required for the Research Goals of this proposal, one for two HDO (335 GHz), and one for the SO, SO2, H2SO4 window.   A third window is required for 12CO.  While 12CO observations are not critical to proposal objectives, they will provide value-added science, and do not compromise any aspect of the SOx, HDO related research objectives. ACA and 12-m observations may be scheduled independently within the Jun1-July1, 2014 window.  They do NOT need to be simultaneous. See Science Justification for details.

Required Spatial Resolution and Sensitivity:  
0.45'' spatial resolution is required to map the day-to-night cross-terminator transition with sufficient resolution to map local time variation within the narrow nightside crescent as well as 
across the terminator.  At the targeted phase, 0.45'' resolution provides this for latitudes 50S-50N, or more (4-8 pixels at equator; 3-5 pixels at 50S, 50N). Fig 1 (cycle 0 ALMA map of dayside Venus SO) demonstrates ALMA’s capability to image Venus.  The limb boundary between planet (SO spectra) and cold space (no detection) is well defined. Pixels placed on the 0.8” nightside crescent also show no detection, consistent with 
previous SO observations.

Based upon our experience with SO2, SO, and HDO Venus spectra from the JCMT, a  measurement sensitivity of 0.5 K for SO2 is required for accurate retrieval of  SO2 altitude distributions. 

OT-estimated Time Requirement
The OT estimates that 3.91 hours (total, including 12-m, ACA, and overhead) for each time period (each Science Goal). Total time for 
the project would thus be 7.82 hours. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
