    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Venus atmospheric sulfur chemistry is crucial to the climate and basic structure of the entire atmosphere. SO2 warms the planet as a greenhouse gas. Thick sulfuric acid clouds block all visible light from the surface, and all upwelling IR radiation that reaches them. Photochemical models of upper atmospheric sulfur chemistry from 1982 were unchallenged until 2004, when submm (346.6 GHz, JCMT) measurements began. These eventually contradicted all fundamental model sulfur predictions, and revealed unpredicted patterns of SO, SO2 behavior. Our primary objective is to elucidate one such pattern, diurnal variation of the SO2/SO ratio, with an observational strategy designed to constrain the (unknown) driving mechanisms as a step toward their identification. 
We propose 0.45” mapping 346.6 GHz Venus SOx across both AM (June 2014) and PM (Mar-Apr2015) terminators to measure spatial gradients between night and day chemistries, then derive from them the timescale of the transition, hence timescale of the unidentified driving mechanism. (Dates for Venus phase, diameter.) HDO (335 GHz, water proxy) will be mapped simultaneously, to elucidate the role of water in sulfur chemistry.</prp:abstract>
